<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1939-12-15T20:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1939-12-15T20:00:00-05:00" n="292" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d292">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">893.102 Tientsin/540: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Grew</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-12-16T10:00:00+09:00">December 16, 1939—10
                                        a.m.</date><lb/>[Received December 15—11:25 p.m.]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>681. Our 603, November 15, 5 p.m. I am sending by air mail to
                                Shanghai today for repetition to Department by naval radio the code
                                text of a long telegram<note n="55" xml:id="d292fn55">No. 682,
                                    December 16, 11 a.m., not printed.</note> containing the revised
                                draft of a proposed agreement for the solution of the Tientsin
                                silver question which the British Government would be prepared to
                                accept, together with explanatory comment by my British colleague.
                                This question is still under negotiation here.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>